#Minor inconvenience: The blinking stars appear a bit lower than intended. Is there a way to make them appear directly below the last line of output without any extra spacing? They also seem to push the console down a bit with each blink, and stopped after short while, which was intentional, but I want them to stay longer.
# You answer: To make the blinking stars appear directly below the last line of output without extra spacing, you can adjust the cursor movement commands. Instead of moving the cursor down with a newline character, you can simply print the stars and then move the cursor back up to overwrite them. Here's the adjusted code:
#Question, do I replace the previous code or add this below it? You answer: You should replace the previous blinking code with this adjusted version to achieve the desired effect.
import time
import sys
def blink_stars(blinks, delay):
    for _ in range(blinks):
        # Print stars
        print("*" * 60)
        time.sleep(delay)
        # Move the cursor up to overwrite the stars
        sys.stdout.write("\033[F")  # Move cursor up one line
        sys.stdout.flush()
        # Clear the line
        sys.stdout.write("\033[K")  # Clear to the end of line
        sys.stdout.flush()
        time.sleep(delay)
blink_stars(200, 0.5)  # Blink 10 times with a 0.5 second delay

#Done? Yes, that should achieve the effect you're looking for. The stars will now appear directly below the last line of output without any extra spacing, and they will blink for the specified number of times. If you have any more questions or need further assistance, feel free to ask!
